⚖️ LLM-as-a-Judge Evaluators for Dataset Experiments

 
LLM-as-a-Judge [https://langfuse.com/docs/scores/model-based-evals]evaluations are a simple and versatile way of evaluating LLM
and LLM application outputs. Common use cases of such model-based evals are scoring how concise the answer of a RAG application is
or identifying how correct an answer is based on some ground truth.
 
Datasets [https://langfuse.com/docs/datasets/overview] in Langfuse allow you to create test sets and benchmarks to evaluate the
performance of your LLM application. Until now, Dataset Experiments [https://langfuse.com/docs/datasets/overview] required custom
evaluations added via SDKs or APIs. Starting today, you can use LLM-as-a-Judge Evaluators on the Datasets you maintain in
Langfuse.
 
🔎 Benefits of this Workflow:
 * Compare output with ground truth in a fuzzy way: LLMs can help check for overlaps between ground truth and outputs while being
   more flexible than other approaches.

 * Set up evals once, and then run simple experiments: Experimentation code no longer needs to perform the eval logic as it is
   done by Langfuse.

 * Measure impact before deployment: Assess changes before they reach production.

 * Detect regressions early: Spot and fix issues early in development.

 
🕹️ Get Started: Check out our changelog [https://langfuse.com/changelog/2024-11-19-llm-as-a-judge-for-datasets] post to learn
more and start automated evaluations on your Dataset Experiments.
 

